article.headline: Nebraska 77, Texas A&M 67
article.story: LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- University of Nebraska guard Jake Muhleisen gave his father a special 50th birthday present Wednesday night, breaking out of a season-long slump to score 25 points and lead the Huskers to a 77-67 win over Texas A&M. "I haven't talked to him yet, but I'm sure he's happy" Muhleisen said of his father, David. "He just wants me to go out and have fun. I was just out there having fun and wasn't thinking so much." Muhleisen's 25 points in the game is the second highest total of his career and the most since he suffered a hip injury three years ago at Kansas. The senior guard's performance, hitting six of seven shots from the field, 10 of 11 free throws and pulling down a team-high six rebounds Wednesday impressed Nebraska coach Barry Collier. "He had a few errors, but overall, that was the best game against a Big 12 opponent in his career," Collier said. Nebraska (9-7, 3-3 Big 12) entered the game ranked 308th out of 326 NCAA Division I teams in free throw percentages, averaging just 61.5 percent. But the Huskers won the game at the line, outscoring Texas A&M (13-4, 2-4) by 18. Nebraska shot 10 percent better than its season average Wednesday. With Texas A&M's 34 fouls, Nebraska was at the line 45 times and made 32 shots. "Luckily, we cashed in and did pretty good from the free throw line," said Husker Charles Richardson. "Throughout the season, we haven't been cashing in in big games." But Texas A&M coach Billy Gillispie said the number of fouls wasn't important. He said Nebraska's playing was. "Nebraska was smarter and played to their strengths. We played to our weaknesses," Gillispie said. Nebraska, which never trailed in the game, made 10 of its first 11 tries on the way to opening up a 28-17 lead with 5:35 remaining in the first half. Texas A&M cut the Nebraska lead to five late in the first half. But Muhleisen drove a left-handed reverse layup at the buzzer to put the Huskers up by seven at the half. Muhleisen's three-pointer with 18:21 left gave Nebraska a 40-29 lead. "He was out there strokin' it," Nebraska's John Turek said of Muhleisen. "He had confidence in his jump shot and was hitting his free throws. He's been struggling for part of the year with his confidence. We're just glad to see him come out and have a game like he did tonight." The Aggies were able to cut the lead to single digits several times, coming to within seven on Antoine Wright's 3-point shot with 12:01 left. But Texas A&M never got closer than eight the stretch. "This was two very evenly matched teams," Collier said. "Both have a commitment to defense and both were scoring. We felt like it was going to be a challenge and it was. This was a really important game for us, no question about it." Nebraska is 3-3 in the Big 12 conference for the first time since 1998-99 when the Huskers opened the league season 4-2.
